body:
It seems that closure type inference is causing "borrowed value does not live long enough" errors in places where it shouldent.

```rust
fn main() {
    let closure = |_v| {};
    {
        let x = 1;
        closure(&x);
    }
    {
        let y = 1;
        closure(&y);
    }
}
```

```rust
  --> src\main.rs:7:17
   |
7  |         closure(&x);
   |                 ^^ borrowed value does not live long enough
8  |     }
   |     - `x` dropped here while still borrowed
...
11 |         closure(&y);
   |         ------- borrow later used here
```

However changing the closure definition to 
```rust
let closure = |_v: &_| {};
```
or moving the `a` definition and call into the same scope as the `closure` definition allows it to compile.

I assume what is happening is when `closure` is called with `a`, `closure` is inferred to be `fn(&'1 i32)`, but then `b` is called so it is trying to call `fn(&'1 i32)` with a `&'2 i32`.
But when it is defined as `&_`, the compiler does not infer the lifetime and instead uses hrbt.

